         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">16/9/87. ¶  ¶ I have just received a letter from Professor Naudin, ¶  esteemed Mr Holtze, in which he informs me that all seeds of  ¶ Eucalyptus miniata ¶  that you were so kind as to send germinated ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="de">87.09.16a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="de">To Maurice Holtze</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="de">GRG 19/391, State Records of South Australia, Adelaide.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="de">16/9/87.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ich habe eben einen Brief erhalten, geehrter Herr Holtze, von Prof. Naudin, worin er mir mittheilt, dass alle Samen von Euc. miniata, welche Sie so freundlich waren zu senden, gut keimten, dass aber an der Küste des mittelländischen Meeres, wo doch die Temperatur so milde ist, die Sämlinge zu Grunde gingen, während dort andere Eucalypten gut gedeihen.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Glauben Sie, dass die Euc. miniata an irgend eine besondere Bodenart, vielleicht an </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Kalk</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> gebunden ist? Ich erinnere, dass dies der Eindruck war, den der Baum 1855 &amp; 1856 auf mich machte.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Könnten noch einmal Samen davon erlangt werden? Auch von E. phoenicea, welche ähnliche Rinde und auch scharlach-rothe Blüthen hat, sind die Samen sehr erwünscht. Vielleicht besorgt solche ein Freund weiter östlich. Haben Sie das ächte</seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">old spelling = echte.</p>
               </note>
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Panicum%20spectabile">Panicum spectabile</name> im Wuchs dort? Wenn nicht so will ich Ihnen die Wurzeln in einem Glass Kasten senden. Das Grass ist für </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">tropische Gegenden</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">, selbst für losen Sand, von </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">höchster Wichtigkeit</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">. Wie hat sich bei Ihnen <name key="Medicago%20scutellata">Medicago scutellata</name> und M. orbicularis bewährt! Der "Key" wird im nächsten Monat erscheinen. Darnach will ich auch wieder Pflanzen von </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Ihnen</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> vornehmen</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">Freundlichst grüssend</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">16/9/87.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have just received a letter from Professor Naudin,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found.</p>
               </note> esteemed Mr Holtze, in which he informs me that all seeds of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Eucalyptus%20miniata">Eucalyptus miniata</name>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to M. Holtze, 3 December 1886 (in this edition as 86-12-03b); M to M. Holtze, 30 December 1886; and M to M. Holtze, 7 January 1887.</p>
               </note> that you were so kind as to send germinated well, but that all the seedlings perished at the Mediterranean coast,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See also M to M. Holtze, 3 December 1886 (in this edition as 86-12-03b).</p>
               </note> where the temperature is so mild, while other eucalypts grow well there.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Do you think that <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Eucalyptus%20miniata">Eucalyptus miniata</name>
               </seg> is linked to some particular type of soil, perhaps <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">limestone</hi>
               </seg>? I remember that was the impression I gained of the tree in 1855 and 1856.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">As botanist to the North Australian Exploring Expedition, 1855-6.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Could seeds of it be obtained again? The seeds of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. phoenicea</seg>, which has similar bark and scarlet flowers as well, is also very desirable. Perhaps a friend further east can obtain them. Do you have the true <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Panicum%20spectabile">Panicum spectabile</name>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to M. Holtze, 4 May 1888, and M to M. Holtze, 24 March 1889 (in this edition as 89-03-24a).</p>
               </note> under cultivation there? If not, I will send you roots in a glass case. This grass is of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">greatest importance</hi>
               </seg> for <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">tropical areas</hi>
               </seg>, even on loose sand.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In the 1895 edition of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Select extra-tropical plants</seg> (B95.13.02), M recorded under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Panicum%20spectabile">Panicum spectabile</name>
                     </seg>: 'From Port Darwin largely distributed by the Messrs. Holtze'.</p>
               </note> How have <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Medicago%20scutellata">Medicago scutellata</name>
               </seg> and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. orbicularis</seg> established themselves there? The 'Key'<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B88.13.03.</p>
               </note> will be published next month. After that I will once more take up plants from <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">you</hi>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">With kindest regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; font-size: 10pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eucalyptus%20miniata">Eucalyptus miniata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20orbicularis">Medicago orbicularis</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Medicago%20scutellata">Medicago scutellata</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Panicum%20spectabile">Panicum spectabile</name>
            </p>
         </div>
